    <div class="container">
        <header>
            <h1>Proteins: Functions, Types, and Tests</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">Interactive Science Presentation & Quiz</p>
        </header>
        
        <div class="app-container">
            <!-- Presentation Section -->
            <div class="presentation-container">
                <div class="section-title">
                    <i class="fas fa-microscope"></i> Protein Presentation
                </div>
                
                <div class="slideshow">
                    <!-- Slide 1 -->
                    <div class="slide active">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 1 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Proteins: Functions, Classifications, and Laboratory Tests</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <p>Science Presentation</p>
                            <p><em>(Study of biomolecules essential for life processes)</em></p>
                            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 30px;">
                                <i class="fas fa-dna" style="font-size: 4rem; color: #1a73e8;"></i>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 2 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 2 of 16</div>
                        <h2>What are Proteins?</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <ul>
                                <li>Proteins are <span class="highlight">large organic molecules</span> made of amino acids</li>
                                <li>Contain <span class="highlight">Carbon, Hydrogen, Oxygen, Nitrogen</span> (sometimes Sulfur)</li>
                                <li>Called the <span class="highlight">building blocks of the body</span></li>
                                <li>Essential for <span class="highlight">growth, repair, and regulation</span> of body processes</li>
                                <li>Found in <span class="highlight">all living cells</span></li>
                            </ul>
                            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">
                                <i class="fas fa-atom" style="font-size: 3rem; color: #34a853;"></i>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 3 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 3 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Amino Acids</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Small units</span> that make up proteins</li>
                                <li>Linked together by <span class="highlight">peptide bonds</span></li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">20 common amino acids</span> in living organisms</li>
                                <li>Sequence determines the protein's <span class="highlight">shape and function</span></li>
                                <li>Even one wrong amino acid may change the protein function (<span class="highlight">mutation effect</span>)</li>
                            </ul>
                            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">
                                <div style="display: inline-block; padding: 10px 20px; background-color: #e8f0fe; border-radius: 8px;">
                                    <i class="fas fa-link" style="color: #1a73e8;"></i> Peptide Bond Formation
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 4 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 4 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Levels of Protein Structure</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <ol>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Primary</span> — sequence of amino acids</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Secondary</span> — alpha helix and beta pleated sheet (hydrogen bonding)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Tertiary</span> — 3D folding due to side-chain interactions</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Quaternary</span> — multiple polypeptide chains combined (e.g., hemoglobin)</li>
                            </ol>
                            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">
                                <div style="display: inline-flex; gap: 10px; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center;">
                                    <div style="padding: 8px 15px; background-color: #e8f0fe; border-radius: 5px;">1°</div>
                                    <div style="padding: 8px 15px; background-color: #e6f4ea; border-radius: 5px;">2°</div>
                                    <div style="padding: 8px 15px; background-color: #fce8e6; border-radius: 5px;">3°</div>
                                    <div style="padding: 8px 15px; background-color: #fef7e0; border-radius: 5px;">4°</div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 5 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 5 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Functions of Proteins</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Growth and repair</span> of tissues</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Enzymes</span> (speed up biochemical reactions)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Hormones</span> (chemical messengers)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Transport molecules</span> (carry substances in blood)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Immune defense</span> (antibodies fight pathogens)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Movement</span> (muscle contraction)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Maintain pH and fluid balance</span></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 6 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 6 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Examples of Protein Functions</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <table>
                                <thead>
                                    <tr>
                                        <th>Function</th>
                                        <th>Example</th>
                                    </tr>
                                </thead>
                                <tbody>
                                    <tr>
                                        <td>Enzyme</td>
                                        <td>Amylase (breaks starch)</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr>
                                        <td>Hormone</td>
                                        <td>Insulin (controls blood sugar)</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr>
                                        <td>Transport</td>
                                        <td>Hemoglobin (carries oxygen)</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr>
                                        <td>Defense</td>
                                        <td>Antibodies (fight infection)</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr>
                                        <td>Structural</td>
                                        <td>Collagen (skin & bones)</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr>
                                        <td>Movement</td>
                                        <td>Actin & Myosin (muscles)</td>
                                    </tr>
                                </tbody>
                            </table>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 7 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 7 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Classification of Proteins (By Shape)</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <h3 style="color: #34a853; margin-top: 20px;">Fibrous Proteins</h3>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Long and narrow structure</li>
                                <li>Provide structural support and strength</li>
                                <li>Insoluble in water</li>
                                <li>Example: <span class="highlight">Keratin</span> (hair), <span class="highlight">Collagen</span> (skin)</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <h3 style="color: #34a853; margin-top: 20px;">Globular Proteins</h3>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Rounded compact shape</li>
                                <li>Functional and metabolic roles</li>
                                <li>Usually soluble in water</li>
                                <li>Example: <span class="highlight">Enzymes</span>, <span class="highlight">Hemoglobin</span></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 8 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 8 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Classification (By Composition)</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <h3 style="color: #34a853; margin-top: 20px;">Simple Proteins</h3>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Made only of amino acids</li>
                                <li>Produce only amino acids upon digestion</li>
                                <li>Example: <span class="highlight">Albumin</span> (egg white)</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <h3 style="color: #34a853; margin-top: 20px;">Conjugated Proteins</h3>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Protein + non-protein component (prosthetic group)</li>
                                <li>Needed for specialized function</li>
                                <li>Example: <span class="highlight">Hemoglobin</span> (with iron), <span class="highlight">Lipoprotein</span> (with lipids)</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 9 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 9 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Classification (By Function)</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Structural proteins</span> — support cells and tissues</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Transport proteins</span> — carry molecules in blood or membrane</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Storage proteins</span> — store nutrients (casein in milk)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Enzymatic proteins</span> — catalysts of reactions</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Defensive proteins</span> — antibodies and clotting proteins</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Regulatory proteins</span> — hormones controlling processes</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 10 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 10 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Food Sources of Protein</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Meat and poultry</span> (complete protein)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Fish</span> (high biological value protein)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Eggs</span> (reference protein standard)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Milk and dairy products</span></li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Beans and legumes</span> (plant protein)</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Nuts and seeds</span></li>
                            </ul>
                            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">
                                <i class="fas fa-utensils" style="font-size: 3rem; color: #fbbc04;"></i>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 11 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 11 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Tests for Presence of Protein</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <p>Laboratory tests detect proteins based on chemical reactions. Proteins react due to peptide bonds or amino acid groups.</p>
                            
                            <h3 style="color: #34a853; margin-top: 20px;">Common Tests:</h3>
                            <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Biuret Test</span> — peptide bonds</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Ninhydrin Test</span> — amino acids</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Xanthoproteic Test</span> — aromatic amino acids</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 12 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 12 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Biuret Test</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <p><strong>Principle:</strong> Copper ions react with peptide bonds in alkaline solution</p>
                            <p><strong>Procedure:</strong> Add Biuret reagent (NaOH + CuSO₄)</p>
                            <p><strong>Positive Result:</strong> Violet or purple color</p>
                            <p>Indicates presence of proteins/polypeptides</p>
                            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">
                                <div style="display: inline-block; padding: 10px 20px; background-color: #8a2be2; color: white; border-radius: 8px;">
                                    <i class="fas fa-vial"></i> Violet/Purple Color
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 13 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 13 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Ninhydrin Test</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <p><strong>Principle:</strong> Reacts with free amino groups of amino acids</p>
                            <p><strong>Positive Result:</strong> Blue-violet color (Ruhemann's purple)</p>
                            <p>Used to detect amino acids and small peptides (e.g., fingerprint detection)</p>
                            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">
                                <div style="display: inline-block; padding: 10px 20px; background-color: #6a0dad; color: white; border-radius: 8px;">
                                    <i class="fas fa-fingerprint"></i> Blue-Violet Color
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 14 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 14 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Xanthoproteic Test</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <p><strong>Principle:</strong> Nitric acid reacts with aromatic amino acids (tyrosine, tryptophan, phenylalanine)</p>
                            <p>Heat with nitric acid</p>
                            <p><strong>Positive Result:</strong> Yellow → orange color after adding alkali</p>
                            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">
                                <div style="display: inline-block; padding: 10px 20px; background: linear-gradient(to right, #ffd700, #ff8c00); color: #333; border-radius: 8px;">
                                    <i class="fas fa-flask"></i> Yellow → Orange Color
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 15 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 15 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Summary</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content">
                            <ul>
                                <li>Proteins are <span class="highlight">polymers of amino acids</span></li>
                                <li>Perform <span class="highlight">structural and metabolic functions</span></li>
                                <li>Classified by <span class="highlight">shape, composition, and function</span></li>
                                <li>Detected using chemical tests: <span class="highlight">Biuret, Ninhydrin, Xanthoproteic</span></li>
                            </ul>
                            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 30px;">
                                <i class="fas fa-check-circle" style="font-size: 4rem; color: #34a853;"></i>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <!-- Slide 16 -->
                    <div class="slide">
                        <div class="slide-number">Slide 16 of 16</div>
                        <h2>Thank You!</h2>
                        <div class="slide-content" style="text-align: center; padding-top: 80px;">
                            <i class="fas fa-graduation-cap" style="font-size: 5rem; color: #1a73e8; margin-bottom: 30px;"></i>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; color: #333;">Now test your knowledge with the quiz!</p>
                            <div style="margin-top: 40px;">
                                <button class="btn" onclick="startQuiz()">
                                    <i class="fas fa-play-circle"></i> Start Quiz
                                </button>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
